---
// src/pages/about.astro — About page (English)
import MainLayout from '../layouts/MainLayout.astro';

const lang = 'en';
---

<MainLayout title="About Us | Chinese SDGs Institute" description="Learn about the mission, vision, and work of the Chinese SDG Institute." lang={lang}>
  <main class="pt-24 md:pt-40 pb-16 md:pb-32">
    <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12">
      <nav class="flex items-center gap-2 text-[10px] font-label uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-on-surface-variant mb-6 md:mb-8">
        <span>Institute</span>
        <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-[12px]">chevron_right</span>
        <span class="text-primary font-bold">About</span>
      </nav>

      <h1 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-headline font-extrabold tracking-tight text-on-surface leading-[1.1] mb-6 md:mb-8">
        About the Chinese SDG Institute
      </h1>

      <p class="text-lg text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed mb-16 max-w-2xl">
        Fostering a new generation of leaders dedicated to sustainable development, tailored for the unique landscape of China.
      </p>

      <div class="article-body">
        <h2>Our Mission: Localizing Global Goals</h2>
        <p>
          The Chinese SDG Institute is a youth-led, non-profit initiative born from a collective passion for a sustainable future. Our core mission is to bridge the gap between the global Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) and the tangible realities of local communities across China. We believe that the grand ambitions outlined in the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development can only be realized through grassroots action, informed by deep, nuanced understanding of regional contexts.
        </p>
        <p>
          In a world guided by the comprehensive frameworks championed by global bodies like the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), our role is not one of formal affiliation, but of inspired action. We operate as an independent platform, aligning our efforts with the global dialogue and dedicating ourselves to translating its universal principles into impactful, region-specific projects. We are a volunteer-driven collective of students, young professionals, and academics committed to empowering the next generation of change-makers.
        </p>

        <h2>Our Vision: A Tapestry of Local Solutions</h2>
        <p>
          We envision a future where every young person in China sees themselves as a vital contributor to the sustainable development narrative. Our vision is not of a single, top-down solution, but a rich tapestry woven from thousands of local innovations. We see a future where a student in Yunnan is pioneering sustainable agriculture techniques tailored to the region's biodiversity, a high schooler in Shanghai is developing a community recycling program that addresses urban waste, and a university team in Gansu is researching water conservation strategies for arid landscapes.
        </p>
        <p>
          This future is built on the principle that sustainable development is not an abstract concept, but a practical, everyday pursuit. The Chinese SDG Institute aims to be the catalyst for this movement, creating a self-sustaining ecosystem of knowledge, collaboration, and action.
        </p>

        <h2>Our Approach: From Theory to Action</h2>
        <p>
          Understanding the SDGs is the first step; acting on them is what creates change. The Chinese SDG Institute operates on a dual-track approach that combines rigorous academic inquiry with hands-on community engagement. We are fundamentally a volunteer-based organization, harnessing the energy, creativity, and intellectual curiosity of our nation's youth.
        </p>
        <p>
          Our primary method is to encourage and facilitate research that is both academically sound and deeply practical. We guide students to move beyond generic understandings of sustainability and to ask critical questions: What does "Quality Education" (SDG 4) mean in the context of rural Guizhou versus urban Beijing? How can "Sustainable Cities and Communities" (SDG 11) be advanced in rapidly developing Tier-2 cities?
        </p>
        <p>To achieve this, we have developed two core pillars of activity:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Events and Workshops:</strong> We organize a variety of events, from online seminars with development experts to in-person workshops and local "SDG Action" competitions held in cities across mainland China. These gatherings are designed to be interactive and collaborative, providing a space for students to connect with mentors, learn practical research methodologies, and develop their own project proposals.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Commissioned Research and Publications:</strong> We believe in providing a platform for young voices to be heard. The Institute actively commissions articles, research papers, and case studies from promising high school and university students. Our volunteer editorial team works closely with these young authors to refine their arguments and prepare their work for publication.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <h2>Why a Local Focus?</h2>
        <p>
          China's vast and diverse landscape presents a unique mosaic of development challenges. A one-size-fits-all approach to sustainability is not only ineffective but can be counterproductive. The environmental priorities of a coastal manufacturing hub are vastly different from those of an agricultural province in the central plains or a nomadic region in the west.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is why our emphasis on "region-specific" research is paramount. By encouraging students to investigate their own backyards, we foster a sense of ownership and relevance. The SDGs cease to be a distant set of goals from a global institution and become a practical lens through which students can understand and improve their immediate environment.
        </p>

        <h2>Join Us</h2>
        <p>
          The Chinese SDG Institute is more than just an organization; it is a community. Whether you are a high school student with a budding interest in environmental science, a university student passionate about social justice, a young professional looking to volunteer your expertise, or an educator who wants to empower your students, there is a place for you here.
        </p>
        <p>
          Together, we can build a movement of informed, passionate, and active young leaders who will drive the future of sustainable development in China, one community at a time.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>
</MainLayout>
